<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910624-0015</DOCNO><DOCID>910624-0015.</DOCID><HL>   Technology:   U.S. Proposes That Organs   Be Tested for AIDS Virus</HL><DATE>06/24/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B7</SO><MS>CONSUMER NON-CYCLICAL (NCY)TECHNOLOGY (TEC)</MS><IN>HEALTH CARE PROVIDERS, MEDICINE, DENTISTRY (HEA)MEDICAL AND BIOTECHNOLOGY, GENETIC RESEARCH, PROSTHETICS (MTC)</IN><GV>HEALTH AND HUMAN SERVICES (HHS)</GV><RE>NORTH AMERICA (NME)UNITED STATES (US)</RE><LP>   WASHINGTON -- The Department of Health and Human Servicesproposed a new federal regulation requiring that human organsbe tested for the AIDS virus before they are supplied tohospitals for transplantations.   Under the proposed rule, published in the FederalRegister, tissue banks must guarantee that tests have beenconducted to ensure the organs are free of the virus thatcauses acquired immune deficiency syndrome.</LP><TEXT>   The rule comes in the wake of recent reports that at leasta half-dozen people may have contracted the AIDS virusthrough transplanted organs that were infected.   The department's Health Care Financing Administration willaccept written comments on the rule for 60 days beforedrafting the final regulation.</TEXT></DOC>